Turkey's diplomatic horizons are widening
Long before Turkey began trying to join the European Union, European powers wanted to penetrate deep into the Turkish border.
On the eastern shore of the Bosporus, perhaps just twenty paces in Asia, stands one of the best monuments to this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpa<0xC5><0x9F>a railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in neo-Renaissance style.
That’s what a tourist guide will tell you.
The building sits round at the end of the platforms with a tower on each corner of the facade, looking indistinguishable from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once one gets inside the vaulted cash register, one can no longer doubt the size of the enterprise whose westernmost gateway to the station was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolian-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which became involved late in the game by the empires, intended to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by using this railway, which was supposed to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during the First World War.
Their tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular units.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone
British and colonial troops marched out of Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there's bad news for Hydarpasha Station, too.
In 1917, an explosion of an ammunition train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has been gradually crumbling and history has been bypassing it.
Today, however, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves, at least symbolically, to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development party - the AKP - has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
A new policy is now in place - Turkey is engaged.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To review the parameters of this new policy, I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I was to meet with one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a curvy ride on the tracks that reminded me of the old-world rhythms of the famous Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish metropolis, designed as a new city for the secular state, which wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
In the West, she aroused suspicions, especially in Washington.
The taxi took me to the AKP main tent, an ultra-modern stone and metal building, purposely built in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built department stores and powerhouses, where middle managers in business suits - men and women - meet to make early morning shopping.
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a centre-right politician from almost every other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
“The party’s foreign policy objective is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate vicinity.
“The Cold War was an anomaly,” he said.
Turkey was cut off from its homeland.
Today we have to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
He had to do both.
"But I'm sure there will come a time," I asked, "when may Turkey have to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "didn't want that kind of decision to happen."
Then he stressed what almost everyone I spoke to here said almost by heart: Turkish relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea region are as good for Europe and the United States as they are for Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, take these tracks east to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpa<0xC5><0x9F>a Station, after another mostly waking night, I thought of the two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had watched the construction of this building a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be to find that European ambitions in the Middle East may now be, in large part, in Turkish hands.
And when I was waiting in the harbour for the ferry back over the Bosphorus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe".
So it seems that at least then there was not much doubt about which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
