"Car bee" prevents collisions
This time, Nissan was inspired by nature, specifically bees, to make progress in the development of accident-protective technologies.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the role of flying bees and thus prevents collisions.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Center for Technological Advancement have developed a robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Advancement at the prestigious Tokyo University.
According to Kazuhir Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology, Research and Development of the brand, the BR23C is presented as an extension of the four zones of Nissan’s safety shield.
The robot is tasked to strengthen the ability to prevent collisions in cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of an oval shape, which is very similar to the safety shield of Nissan.
Most important, however, are the folded bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, which allows the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual feature, the engineers designed what they called the Laser Range Finder.
It records obstacles up to a distance of two meters within a 180-degree radius of the BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"The moment an obstacle is detected, the robot will mimic the bee movements and immediately change direction by turning the wheels to the right or even greater angle to prevent collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to respond quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, a robot cannot move up and down or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and to the direction by which it is allowed to rotate its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as in bees.
In addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent the robot from colliding.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and according to these data, it should behave.
It does not require the preservation of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with only two dozen kB of memory.
It may surprise you, but we’re not talking about giga or mega in memory.”
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for instant precipitation prevention, a technology for which Nissan predicts the use of serial cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would guide the driver to the destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
