Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
To re-establish a republic around 21st-century socialism.
This is a joint project by Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez of Venezuela, Eva Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
Last Sunday, the third candidate, following the example of his counterparts and friends, tabled a proposal for a new Constitution.
And his mission is fulfilled, because 64% of voters, according to official results covering 80% of the vote, voted "yes" in the referendum.
According to these results, "No" received 28%, 7% of the votes were invalid and 0.7% of the ballots were empty.
In order to pass the bill, he had to get half the votes plus one.
Two polls conducted near the east of the polling stations and a calculation by NGOs on Sunday predicted a clear "yes" victory, ranging from 63% to 70%.
On the night of Sunday to Monday, Rafael Correa demanded the victory of his draft constitution.
"The Constitution has won the whole line," he assured and congratulated the Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the Guayaquil Governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
It goes without saying that Rafael Correa received congratulations from Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez and Morales, but also from his Chilean counterpart, Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which, according to the Organization of American States (OEA) observation mission, took place calmly, concerned the text of 444 points building up the "new socialism" promoted by the president.
The draft Constitution consecrates the state's power over the economy by reserving to it "development planning" of a country living primarily on the extraction of oil by foreign companies and on the foreign exchange sent by its emigrants.
The Correa-backed proposal, which was elected in 2006, also extends the powers of the head of state, who will be able to serve two consecutive four-year terms and be able to dissolve the House.
Correa has already announced that it will exercise this power and will apply for a new mandate in February 2009.
The constitution, among other things, reinforces the principle of free health and education, which the president began to introduce in a country of 13.9 million people, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, he also expects to ban the presence of foreign troops, thereby ending the agreement between Washington and Quito to use the Ecuadorean base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
