The Benelux government will take over the state of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states will help Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to be in trouble due to the growing impact of the US mortgage crisis, by partial nationalization: the three countries will support a money and insurance institution, which also has a capital stake in Hungary, with a sum of 11.2 billion euros.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed at the highest level, with the participation of the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
Fortis is the first bank in the euro area to enter a major crisis in the context of the international financial market crisis, which has been spreading in waves for more than a year, and the decisions taken in this matter could be seen as precedents in some respects.
In terms of the decision, which was born on Sunday night, all three states will buy out almost half (49 percent) of the bank’s assets there.
The bank will sell some of its equity holdings with absolute certainty, especially the insurance activities purchased last year from Dutch bank ABN Amro.
Bank Fortis shares began to fall sharply last week, in the second half of the week there were already serious signs of the crisis in the institution.
Analysts agree, however, that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to let it go bankrupt.
The company’s securities fell 12 percent to a 14-year low on Friday alone.
Since January, the value of shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Given the current stock prices, the Group’s total market capital value is around <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>14 billion, but this is unrealistic according to the company’s leaders.
The company’s management blames the collapse of Fortis’ shares for the uncertainty in the overseas market associated with the adoption of the US $700 billion package plan.
On Monday, the shares rose slightly.
On Friday, a new CEO, Filip Dierckx, was appointed to the head of the bank.
The monetary institution was also looking for private buyers, but with a more serious offer, no one has so far signed up.
The Belgian government has already announced that investors do not have to worry about losing their money.
There was no panic among the bank’s clients, and the branches were not taken by attack.
In Hungary, Fortis has a separate branch and has also acquired several leasing companies.
The fox in the henhouse
Life and health insurance companies in America, based on people's data on drug purchases, often deny the possibility of concluding an insurance contract with an applicant.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescribing data in any case with the consent of the person concerned.
It must be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the chicken coop to a fox," Richard Dick, the author of the drug-prescribing monitoring program, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make premiums and the amounts paid in the event of an insured event depend on the health status of the applicants, and if the risk is assessed as too high, they will not even conclude insurance with it.
Previously, they sent those concerned for medical examinations and only concluded the contract when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick came up with a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification number, a customer from pharmacies can easily find out what drugs the person has purchased in the last year and a half, from which the program itself draws, how he suffers from the disease and what his health is.
For example, if he regularly buys a large amount of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this refers to the fact that he has practically uncontrollably high blood fat levels, which immediately puts him in the category with a higher risk.
Several versions of the program are in circulation, some also determine the risk factor, so there is almost no work left for the insurance company except for paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include that some drugs can also be used for several purposes, some compounds are, for example, usable against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
From the point of view of commercial insurance companies, these represent a significant risk-increasing factor, while the first mentioned difficulties are not.
For the purpose of requesting and processing data, special companies have been created, which, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, will ask the patient for permission.
They are now being forced to do so by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their negligence so far.
Recently, some companies are also processing the results of laboratory tests, which combine with data on the medicines used, thanks to which they can provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data, at the same time controlling their use will become more and more difficult.
There is a special health data protection law, but its effectiveness applies only to health care providers and insurance companies.
The bill, which will give the authorities the power to control even companies specializing in data provision, is before Congress.
Richard Dick admits that this is not enough: therefore, he has developed his programme so that the transfer of data is bound by the explicit consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that he can hardly refuse the permit in question, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
So chickens are, after all, somewhat reliant on the falcon of goodwill.
